data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

The EF Core Cosmos DB provider **removes the sync-over-async opt-in entirely**. In .NET 10, you could suppress the `InvalidOperationException` with a flag like:

```csharp
options.UseCosmos(..., cosmosOptions =>
    cosmosOptions.AllowSynchronousQueryExecution());
```

In .NET 11, that configuration option is gone. Every synchronous LINQ operator — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` — will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime because the underlying Cosmos DB SDK is async-only and no bridge remains.

## How to fix it

Convert to async all the way through:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
| Sync (broken) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `await ToListAsync()` |
| `First()` | `await FirstAsync()` |
| `Count()` | `await CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `await SaveChangesAsync()` |

The async methods live in `Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore` (imported via `using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;`).

This is an **async-all-the-way** migration — callers of these methods must also become `async`/`await` up through controllers or endpoints. There is no workaround; the Cosmos SDK has no synchronous I/O path.
